properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert For Portions Of The Red River
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Red River at Emerson, Letellier, Ste. Agathe, and within the City of Winnipeg due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-22T12:45:00-05:00

Area: The Red River at Emerson, Letellier, Ste. Agathe, and within the City of Winnipeg
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Northeast winds will continue to strengthen today with gusts up to 90 km/h. Blizzard conditions will then develop early this afternoon when fresh snow begins to fall. The worst conditions are expected to occur this afternoon and evening. The blizzard is expected to end overnight as the falling snow ends and the wind weakens. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-22T06:38:32-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-21T14:39:32-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.4032327554.2019
Area: Resolute
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A low pressure centre currently over the Pacific Ocean will approach Haida Gwaii this afternoon and the North Coast this evening. In its wake, westerly winds with speeds in excess of 90 km/h will develop early this evening. The strongest winds will affect northern Haida Gwaii and northern portions of the North Coast - Coastal regions. The strong winds will ease after midnight. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-22T09:48:49-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-21T17:49:49-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0878497126.2019
Area: Haida Gwaii, North Coast - coastal sections
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rainfall expected tonight. The rain will begin later this afternoon and taper off to a few showers by Tuesday morning. The heaviest rainfall is expected to occur between 5 PM and 10 PM EDT. Total rainfall amounts of 40 to 50 mm are expected. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Watch for possible washouts near rivers, creeks and culverts. This area of rain is associated with a strengthening Colorado low that will track into Northern Ontario on Tuesday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-22T07:14:53-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-21T15:15:53-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.3866349866.2019
Area: City of Thunder Bay, Cloud Bay - Dorion, Kakabeka Falls - Whitefish Lake - Arrow Lake

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. An intense low pressure system near Gjoa Haven is giving strong east winds to Arctic Bay - which may at times reach the warning threshold of 70 gusting 90 km/h throughout the overnight and morning hours. Winds should start diminishing this afternoon as the low weakens somewhat. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
